{{Orphan|date=February 2017}}
{{Tropicalcyclone}}
'''Tropical cyclones''' are named for historical reasons to avoid confusion when communicating with the public, as more than one tropical cyclone can exist at a time. Names are drawn in order from predetermined lists and are usually assigned to tropical cyclones with one-, three- or ten-minute windspeeds of more than {{convert|65|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}. However, standards vary from basin to basin with some tropical depressions named in the Western Pacific whilst tropical cyclones have to have gale-force winds occurring more than halfway around the center within the Australian and Southern Pacific regions.
This is a list of storm names beginning with the letter U&ndash;Z.
==U== *{{Anchor|Uding}}Uding :*[[1966 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Nancy .28Uding.29|1966]] - PAGASA name for Tropical Storm Nancy, which killed 32&nbsp;people while crossing the Philippines :*[[1970 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Marge .28Uding.29|1970]] - PAGASA name for Tropical Storm Marge, which crossed the central Philippines :*[[1974 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Della .28Uding.29|1974]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Della, which brushed Luzon before hitting Vietnam :*[[1977 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Kim .28Unding.29|1977]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Kim, which killed 102&nbsp;people when it struck Luzon; 47 of the casualties were related to a hotel fire during the storm :*[[1978 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Kit|1978]] - PAGASA name for Tropical Storm Kit, which formed west of the Philippines and struck Vietnam :*[[1982 Pacific typhoon season#Super Typhoon Mac .28Uding.29|1982]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Mac, which struck Guam and remained well east of the Philippines :*[[1986 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Ida .28Uding.29|1986]] - PAGASA name for Tropical Storm Ida, which killed two people while crossing the central Philippines :*[[1994 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Gladys .28Uding.29|1994]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Gladys, which struck Taiwan and Fujian *{{Anchor|Uleki}}[[Hurricane Uleki|Uleki (1988)]] - caused high surf in Hawaii that killed two people *{{Anchor|Ula}}[[Cyclone Ula|Ula (2016)]] - long-lived and powerful cyclone that affected Tonga, Fiji, and Vanuatu *{{Anchor|Ulika}}[[2016 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Ulika|Ulika (2016)]] - hurricane that dissipated southeast of Hawaii *{{Anchor|Ulpiang}}Ulpiang :*[[1996 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Dale .28Ulpiang.29|1996]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Dale, which passed south of Japan :*[[2000 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Depression Ulpiang|2000]] - PAGASA name for a tropical depression that killed 3&nbsp;people while moving through the Philippines *{{Anchor|Ului}}[[Cyclone Ului|Ului (2010)]] - intense tropical cyclone that passed through the Solomon Islands and later struck eastern Australia *{{Anchor|Ulysses}}[[Typhoon Dolphin (2008)|Ulysses (2008)]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Dolphin, which killed 47&nbsp;people when it sank the ''M/Bca Mae Jan'' cargo ship *{{Anchor|Uma}}[[1986–87 South Pacific cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Uma|Uma (1987)]] - killed 50 people when it struck the island of Vanuatu in the South Pacific *{{Anchor|Una}}Una :*[[1964–65 Australian region cyclone season|1965]] - short-lived cyclone that passed south of Christmas Island :*[[1973–74 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Una|1973]] - tropical storm that struck Queensland *{{Anchor|Unala}}[[2013 Pacific hurricane season#Tropical Storm Unala|Unala (2013)]] - tropical storm that developed near the International Date line *{{Anchor|Undang}}Undang :*[[1964 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Marie .28Undang.29|1964]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Marie, which interacted and was absorbed by [[1964 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Kathy .28Welpring.29|Typhoon Kathy]] :*[[1972 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Therese .28Undang.29|1972]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Therese, which killed 90 people in the Philippines and Vietnam :*[[1976 Pacific typhoon season|1976]] - PAGASA name for a tropical depression :*[[1980 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Percy .28Undang.29|1980]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Percy, which struck Taiwan and Fujian :*[[1984 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Agnes .28Undang.29|1984]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Agnes, which killed over 1,000&nbsp;people when it moved through the Philippines and Vietnam *{{Anchor|Unding}}Unding :*[[1965 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Rose .28Unding.29|1965]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Rose, which brushed northern Luzon before striking southern China :*[[Typhoon Muifa (2004)|2004]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Muifa, which killed 108&nbsp;people in the Philippines and Vietnam *{{Anchor|Unsang}}[[Typhoon Ruby (1988)|Unsang (1988)]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Ruby, which killed over 300&nbsp;people in the Philippines, mostly related to the sinking of the ''[[MV Doña Marilyn]]'' *{{Anchor|Unsing}}Unsing :*[[1981 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Fabian .28Unsing.29|1981]] - PAGASA name for Tropical Storm Fabian, which crossed the Philippines and Vietnam :*[[1985 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Hope .28Unsing.29|1985]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Hope, which dissipated east of Luzon :*[[1989 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Hunt .28Unsing.29|1989]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Hunt, which killed 11&nbsp;people while crossing Luzon :*[[1993 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Zola .28Unsing.29|1993]] - moved across Japan *{{Anchor|Upala}}[[2000 Pacific hurricane season#Tropical Storm Upana|Upana (2000)]] - short-lived storm south of Hawaii that redeveloped in the western Pacific Ocean *{{Anchor|Upia}}[[2001–02 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Upia|Upia (2002)]] - short-lived storm east of Papua New Guinea *{{Anchor|Urduja}}Urduja :*[[2009 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Depression 27W .28Urduja.29|2009]] - PAGASA name for a tropical depression that killed four people in the Philippines :*[[Typhoon Francisco (2013)|2013]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Francisco, which developed near Guam and passed south of Japan *{{Anchor|Uriah}}[[2015–16 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Uriah|Uriah (2016)]] - moved across much of the southern Indian Ocean *{{Anchor|Uring}}Uring :*[[1967 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Dinah .28Uring.29|1967]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Dinah, which struck Japan :*[[Typhoon Rose (1971)|1971]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Rose, which struck Luzon before its deadly landfall near Hong Kong :*[[1979 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Sarah .28Trining-Uring.29|1979]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Sarah, which struck Vietnam and moved back toward the Philippines :*[[1983 Pacific typhoon season#Super Typhoon Marge .28Uring.29|1983]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Marge, an intense typhoon that recurved northeast of the Philippines :*[[Tropical Storm Thelma|1991]] - PAGASA name for Tropical Storm Thelma, which killed over 5,000 people while crossing the Philippines, mostly in the city of [[Ormoc]] *{{Anchor|Urmil}}[[Cyclone Urmil (2006)|Urmil (2006)]] - tropical cyclone in the South Pacific that left minor damage on Tonga *{{Anchor|Ursula}}Ursula :*[[1940–49 Pacific typhoon seasons#Typhoon Ursula|1945]] - typhoon that struck Taiwan and China :*[[1971–72 South Pacific cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Ursula|1971]] - persisted near the Solomon Islands :*[[1997–98 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Ursula|1998]] - struck the [[Tuamotus]] island group in [[French Polynesia]], destroying several houses *{{Anchor|Usagi}}Usagi :*[[2001 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Usagi|2001]] - tropical storm that hit Vietnam :*[[2007 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Usagi|2007]] - typhoon that hit southwestern Japan :*[[Typhoon Usagi (2013)|2013]] - passed between Luzon and Taiwan before hitting the Chinese province of Guangdong, leaving US$4.33&nbsp;billion in damage *{{Anchor|Usha}}[[1993–94 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Usha|Usha (1994)]] - moved through Vanuatu *{{Anchor|Utor}}Utor :*[[2001 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Utor .28Feria.29|2001]] - passed north of Luzon and struck Guangdong, killing 197 people :*[[Typhoon Utor (2006)|2006]] - brought additional destruction to the central Philippines following the deadly [[Typhoon Durian]] :*[[Typhoon Utor|2013]] - damaging typhoon in central Philippines and Guangdong :*[[2003 Pacific typhoon season#Other storms|2003]] - short-lived depression that struck [[Palawan]]; name given by PAGASA
==V== *{{Anchor|Vae}}[[1952 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Vae|Vae (1952)]] - typhoon that struck Vietnam *{{Anchor|Vaianu}}[[Cyclone Vaianu (2006)|Vaianu (2006)]] - caused minor damage in Tonga *{{Anchor|Val}}Val :*[[1974–75 South Pacific cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Val|1975]] - meandered near Fiji and Wallis and Futuna :*[[1979–80 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Val|1980]] - passed over Wallis and Futuna :*[[1982 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Tess.E2.80.93Val .28Deling.29|1982]] - reformation of Tropical Storm Tess, which hit Hong Kong :*[[1985 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Val .28Narsing.29|1985]] - passed south of Taiwan and dissipated over Guangdong :*[[1988 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Val .28Apiang.29|1988]] - late season storm that dissipated northeast of the Philippines :*[[Cyclone Val|1991]] - powerful cyclone that left over US$250&nbsp;million in damage in Samoa and American Samoa :*[[1992 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Val|1992]] - remained east of Japan :*[[1995 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Val .28Neneng.29|1995]] - took erratic track south of Japan before dissipating northeast of the Philippines *{{Anchor|Vamco}}Vamco :*[[2003 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Vamco .28Manang.29|2003]] - hit Zhejiang in eastern China, causing damage to houses and farms :*[[2009 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Vamco|2009]] - typhoon that remained southeast of Japan :*[[Tropical Storm Vamco (2015)|2015]] - struck eastern Vietnam, killing 15 people *{{Anchor|Vamei}}[[Tropical Storm Vamei|Vamei (2001)]] - formed within {{convert|160|km|mi|abbr=on}} north of the [[equator]], a record-low latitude *{{Anchor|Valerie}}[[1962 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Valerie|Valerie (1962)]] - hurricane that struck western Mexico *{{Anchor|Vanessa}}Vanessa :*[[1975–76 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Vanessa|1976]] - meandered off the northwest coast of Australia :*[[1981 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Vanessa|1981]] - remained well east of Japan :*[[1984 Pacific typhoon season#Super Typhoon Vanessa .28Reming.29|1984]] - intense typhoon that killed 64 people in the Philippines, despite remaining well east of the country :*[[1988 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Vanessa .28Edeng.29|1988]] - moved across the Philippines and struck southeastern China :*[[1991 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Vanessa .28Bebeng.29|1991]] - moved across the Philippines and dissipated in the South China Sea :*[[1994 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Vanessa .28Loleng.29|1994]] - steered by the larger [[1994 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Tim .28Iliang.29|Typhoon Tim]], it meandered off the west coast of Luzon, where it killed three people *{{Anchor|Vance}}Vance :*[[Hurricane Vance (1990)|1990]] – looped off the southwest coast of Mexico :*[[Cyclone Vance|1999]] – powerful cyclone that wrecked 70% of the city of [[Exmouth, Western Australia]] :*[[Hurricane Vance (2014)|2014]] – a late-season Category 2 hurricane that weakened before affecting Mexico *{{Anchor|Vania}}Vania :*[[1994–95 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Vania|1994]] - moved through Vanuatu :*[[Cyclone Vania|2011]] - struck New Caledonia around the same time that a [[Richter magnitude scale|M7.0]] earthquake affected the region *{{Anchor|Vardah}}[[Cyclone Vardah|Vardah (2016)]] - cyclone that killed 38&nbsp;people when it struck near [[Chennai]], India *{{Anchor|Vaughn}}[[1999–2000 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Vaughan|Vaughn (2000)]] - tropical storm that dissipated over Queensland *{{Anchor|Veena}}[[1982–83 South Pacific cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Veena|Veena (1983)]] - damaging cyclone that moved through French Polynesia *{{Anchor|Veli}}Veli :*[[1986–87 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Veli|1987]] - affected Vanuatu days after the damaging strike of [[1986–87 South Pacific cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Uma|Cyclone Uma]] :*[[1997–98 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Veli|1998]] - cyclone in the South Pacific that caused minor wave damage to French Polynesia *{{Anchor|Velma}}[[1983 Pacific hurricane season#Tropical Storm Velma|Velma (1983)]] - short-lived tropical storm off the southwest coast of Mexico *{{Anchor|Vera}}Vera :*[[1951 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Vera|1951]] - tropical storm that remained east of Japan :*[[1956 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Vera|1956]] - typhoon that struck the Philippines, Hainan, and Vietnam :*[[Typhoon Vera|1959]] - strongest and deadliest typhoon on record in Japan, killing around 5,000&nbsp;people :*[[1962 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Vera|1962]] - typhoon struck the Japanese island of Kyushu :*[[1965 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Vera .28Daling.29|1965]] - short-lived tropical storm that struck the eastern Philippines :*[[1967 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Vera|1967]] - tropical storm that remained east of Japan :*[[1971 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Vera .28Karing.29|1971]] - minimal typhoon that remained away from landmasses :*[[1973 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Vera .28Openg.29|1973]] - moved across southern Philippines :*[[1973–74 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Vera|1974]] - developed east of Australia and progressed southeastward :*[[1977 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Vera .28Huling.29|1977]] - rapidly developing typhoon that killed 25 people when it struck Taiwan and eastern China :*[[1979 Pacific typhoon season#Super Typhoon Vera .28Yayang.29|1979]] - powerful typhoon that weakened before hitting Luzon :*[[Typhoon Vera (1983)|1983]] - deadly typhoon that crossed the Philippines and Hainan, killing 127 people :*[[1986 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Vera .28Loleng.29|1986]] - considered two storms by the JTWC and one by the JMA; the typhoon took an erratic track before hitting South Korea, killing 25 people :*[[1989 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Vera .28Pining.29|1989]] - struck Zhejiang in eastern China, killing 500 people as a tropical storm *{{Anchor|Vern}}[[1977–78 Australian region cyclone season#Cyclone Vern|Vern (1978)]] - hit Western Australia *{{Anchor|Verna}}Verna :*[[1940–49 Pacific typhoon seasons#Tropical Storm Verna|1945]] - tropical storm that moved across China's [[Hainan]] island :*[[1976–77 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Verna|1977]] - late-season cyclone that dissipated near Australia's [[Northern Territory]] *{{Anchor|Verne}}Verne :*[[1991 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Verne|1991]] - passed north of Guam :*[[1994 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Verne .28Delang.29|1994]] - passed near Guam and became an intense typhoon in the Philippine Sea *{{Anchor|Vernon}}Vernon :*[[1980 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Vernon|1980]] - typhoon that remained east of Japan :*[[1984 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Vernon|1984]] - caused flooding in Vietnam :*[[1985–86 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Vernon|1986]] - developed and dissipated northeast of Australia :*[[1987 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Vernon .28Diding.29|1987]] - passed northeast of Luzon and later struck Taiwan :*[[1990 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Vernon|1990]] - typhoon that remained east of Japan :*[[1993 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Vernon|1993]] - typhoon that paralleled the east coast of Japan *{{Anchor|Vicente}}Vicente :*[[Tropical Storm Vicente (2005)|2005]] - hit eastern Vietnam, killing 22&nbsp;people :*[[Typhoon Vicente (2012)|2012]] - rapidly intensifying typhoon that struck near Hong Kong :*[[Tropical Storm Vicente (2018)|2018]] - tiny tropical storm which formed south of Guatemala *{{Anchor|Vicki}}[[1998 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Vicki .28Gading.29|Vicki (1998)]] - crossed Luzon and Japan, killing 108&nbsp;people, mostly related to the sinking of the [[MV Princess of the Orient]] *{{Anchor|Vicky}}Vicky :*[[1971–72 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Vicky|1972]] - struck Western Australia :*[[2001–02 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Vicky|2001]] - short-lived storm in the South Pacific Ocean *{{Anchor|Victor}}Victor :*[[1985–86 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Victor|1986]] - intense cyclone off Western Australia :*[[1997 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Victor .28Goring.29|1997]] - killed 655 people when it struck the Chinese province of Guangdong :*[[1997–98 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Victor-Cindy|1998]] - formed from the remnants of [[Cyclone Katrina]], and was later renamed [[1997–98 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season#Other storms|Cindy]] upon entering the south-west Indian Ocean; lasted 50&nbsp;days from genesis of Katrina to dissipation of Cindy :*[[2015–16 South Pacific cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Victor|2016]] - formed near the Cook Islands *{{Anchor|Victoria}}Victoria :*[[1965 Pacific hurricane season#Tropical Storm Victoria|1965]] - developed off the southwest coast of Mexico :*[[2012–13 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Victoria|2013]] - remained well west of Australia *{{Anchor|Vida}}[[1974–75 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Vida|Vida (1975)]] - damaged houses and churches near [[Perth, Western Australia]] *{{Anchor|Vince}}Vince :*[[Hurricane Vince|Vince (2005)]] - first Atlantic tropical cyclone on record to strike Europe, which hit southwestern Spain in October 2005 :*[[2010–11 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Vince|2011]] - formed and dissipated northwest of Western Australia *{{Anchor|Vincent}}Vincent :*[[1989–90 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Vincent|1990]] - moved around Western Australia :*[[2000–01 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Vincent|2001]] - dissipated over Western Australia *{{Anchor|Vinta}}Vinta :*[[Typhoon Nida (2009)|2009]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Nida, the strongest storm of the season :*[[Typhoon Krosa (2013)|2013]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Krosa, which killed four people while crossing northern Luzon *{{Anchor|Viola}}Viola :*[[1953 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Viola|1953]] - passed south of Taiwan before moving to the northeast and developing into an intense typhoon :*[[1958 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Viola|1958]] - brushed Guam and remained east of Japan :*[[1961 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Depression Viola|1961]] - short-lived storm near southern Vietnam :*[[1964 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Viola .28Konsing.29|1964]] - struck near Hong Kong, leaving thousands homeless while also ending a 2 year drought :*[[1966 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Viola|1966]] - moved across Japan, capsized three ships :*[[1969 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Viola .28Elang.29|1969]] - killed thousands of people in Guangdong in southeastern China :*[[1972 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Viola|1972]] - remained east of Japan :*[[1975 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Viola .28Gening.29|1975]] - formed and dissipated northeast of the Philippines :*[[1978 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Viola .28Esang.29|1978]] - typhoon that dissipated northeast of the Philippines :*[[1979–80 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Viola-Claudette|1979]] - formed in the Australian basin and was renamed Claudette after crossing 90º&nbsp;E *{{Anchor|Violet}}Violet :*[[1955 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Violet|1955]] - January typhoon that struck Mindanao in the Philippines :*[[1959 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Depression Violet|1959]] - tropical depression near southeastern Vietnam :*[[1961 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Violet|1961]] - killed 2 people and wrecked two ships in Japan :*[[1964 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Violet|1964]] - struck central Vietnam as a typhoon :*[[1967 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Violet .28Karing.29|1967]] - typhoon that hit northeastern Luzon :*[[1970 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Violet .28Heling.29|1970]] - tropical storm that crossed the Philippine island of Luzon and the Chinese coast in Guangdong :*[[1972 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Violet|1972]] - late-season tropical storm near the Marshall Islands :*[[1976 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Violet .28Lusing.29|1976]] - tropical storm that killed two people when it struck Hainan and Guangdong in China :*[[1994–95 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Violet|1995]] - dissipated off Australia's east coast near New South Wales :*[[1996 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Violet .28Osang.29|1996]] - brushed southeastern Japan as a typhoon *{{Anchor|Violeta}}[[2004 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Merbok .28Violeta.29|Violeta (2004)]] - local name for Tropical Storm Merbok, which killed 31 people in the Philippines *{{Anchor|Vipa}}[[2001 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Vipa|Vipa (2001)]] - typhoon that passed southeast of Japan *{{Anchor|Virgil}}Virgil :* [[Hurricane Virgil (1992)|1992]] – a late-season category 4 hurricane which struck southwestern Mexico, causing minimal damage. :* [[1999 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Virgil|1999]] – small tropical cyclone southeast of Japan *{{Anchor|Virginia}}Virginia :*[[Typhoon Virginia (1957)|1957]] – Category 5 typhoon. Killed 86 people and caused extensive damage in Taiwan and southern Japan in late June :*[[Typhoon Virginia (1960)|1960]] – Category 2 typhoon. Killed 2 people when it hit Shikoku and Honshū island in Japan during August :*[[Tropical Storm Virginia (1963)|1963]] – moderate tropical storm that was assigned the [[PAGASA]] name '''Etang''' :*[[Typhoon Virginia (1965)|1965]] – minimal Category 1 typhoon :*[[Tropical Storm Virginia (1968)|1968]] – tropical storm that crossed from the western Pacific to the central Pacific :*[[Typhoon Virginia (1971)|1971]] – struck the Japanese coast, killed 56 people due to numerous landslides :*[[Typhoon Virginia (1974)|1974]] – moderate Category 1 typhoon that never affected land :*[[Typhoon Virginia (1978)|1978]] – brushed eastern Japan, but the effects were unknown *{{Anchor|Viring}}[[2003 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Melor .28Viring.29|Viring (2003)]] - PAGASA name for Tropical Storm Melor, which struck Luzon and killed four people *{{Anchor|Vivian}}[[1985 Pacific hurricane season#Tropical Storm Vivian|Vivian (1985)]] - short-lived tropical storm to the southwest of the Baja California peninsula *{{Anchor|Vivienne}}Vivienne :*[[1971–72 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Vivienne|1971]] - South Pacific tropical cyclone :*[[1983–84 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Vivienne-Fanja|1984]] - developed southwest of Indonesia, and was renamed Tropical Cyclone Fanja upon crossing 80º&nbsp;E :*[[2004–05 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Vivienne|2005]] - short-lived storm off the northwest coast of Western Australia *{{Anchor|Viyaru}}[[Cyclone Viyaru|Viyaru (2013)]] - cyclonic storm that killed 107&nbsp;people in Indonesia, Sri Lanka, Bangladesh, and Myanmar; operationally known as Cyclone Mahasen *{{Anchor|Vongfong}}Vongfong :*[[Tropical Storm Vongfong (2002)|2002]] - tropical storm that struck the Chinese province of Guangdong, killing 41&nbsp;people :*[[Tropical Storm Vongfong (2008)|2008]] - tropical storm that passed east of Japan :*[[Typhoon Vongfong (2014)|2014]] - moved through Japan, caused sinking of [[Ocean Researcher V]] off Taiwan
