]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Agnes, which struck Taiwan :*[[Typhoon Tip|1979]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Tip, the [[List of the most intense tropical cyclones|strongest tropical cyclone worldwide]] recorded by atmospheric pressure :*[[1983 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Orchid .28Warling.29|1983]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Orchid, which killed 170 people when it drifted off the eastern Philippines, mostly related to the sinking of the ''MV Dona Cassandra'' :*[[1991 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Wilda .28Warling.29|1991]] - PAGASA name for Tropical Storm Wilda, which crossed the central Philippines *{{Anchor|Warren}}Warren :*[[1981 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Warren|1981]] - struck Hainan Island and Vietnam :*[[1984 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Warren .28Toyang.29|1984]] - meandered in the South China Sea due to the larger [[1984 Pacific typhoon season#Super Typhoon Vanessa .28Reming.29|Typhoon Vanessa]] :*[[1988 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Warren .28Huaning.29|1988]] - struck southeastern China, where it destroyed 13,000 homes and killed 17 :*[[1994–95 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Warren|1995]] - struck Australia's [[Northern Territory]] *{{Anchor|Wasa}}[[Cyclone Wasa–Arthur|Wasa (1991)]] - powerful cyclone that left heavy damage in French Polynesia, later renamed Arthur *{{Anchor|Washi}}Washi :*[[2005 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Washi|2005]] - struck Hainan and Vietnam :*[[Tropical Storm Washi|2011]] - deadly late-season Philippine tropical storm, killed at least 1,268&nbsp;people *{{Anchor|Wati}}[[2005–06 South Pacific cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Wati|Wati (2006)]] - approached and moved southeastward away from the east coast of Australia *{{Anchor|Watoria}}[[1975–76 Australian region cyclone season#Cyclone Watorea|Watoria (1976)]] - moved along the east coast of Australia *{{Anchor|Wayne}}Wayne :*[[1979 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Wayne (Ading)|1979]] - dissipat