stern Philippines *{{Anchor|Yanni}}[[1998 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Yanni .28Heling.29|Yanni (1998)]] - killed 50 people when it stalled over South Korea *{{Anchor|Yanyan}}[[2003 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Yanyan|Yanyan (2003)]] - January tropical storm northwest of Marshall Islands *{{Anchor|Yasi}}Yasi :*[[1995–96 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Yasi|1996]] - tropical storm that brought heavy rainfall to Tonga in the South Pacific :*[[Cyclone Yasi|2011]] - powerful cyclone that struck Queensland, left over US$3&nbsp;billion in damage in Australia to become one of the country's costliest natural disasters *{{Anchor|Yayang}}Yayang :*[[1967 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Freda .28Yayang.29|1967]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Freda, which developed over the Philippines and later struck Vietnam :*[[1971 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Bess .28Yayang.29|1971]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Bess, which struck Taiwan and Fujian :*[[1979 Pacific typhoon season#Super Typhoon Vera .28Yayang.29|1979]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Vera, an intense storm that weakened before hitting Luzon :*[[1983 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Percy .28Yayang.29|1983]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Percy, which formed in the South China Sea and interacted with [[1983 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Orchid .28Warling.29|Typhoon Orchid]] on the east side of the Philippines *{{Anchor|Yates}}[[1996 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Yates .28Paring.29|Yates (1996)]] - intense typhoon that struck Northern Marianas Islands *{{Anchor|Yeyeng}}Yeyeng :*[[1965 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Wendy .28Yeyeng.29|1965]] - PAGASA name for Tropical Storm Wendy, which remained east of Japan :*[[1977 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Mary .28Yeyeng.29|1977]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Mary, which until early January 1978 and dissipated over the Philippines :*[[1981 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Hazen .28Yeyeng.29|1981]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Hazen, which moved across the central Philippines :*[[1989 Pacific typhoon season#Other storms|1989]] - final PAGASA tropical depression of the season :*[[1993 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Becky .28Yeyeng.29|1993]] - PAGASA name for Tropical Storm Becky, which brushed Luzon before striking the Chinese province of Guangdong *{{Anchor|Yoling}}Yoling :*[[1966 Pacific typhoon season#Other Storms|1966]] - PAGASA name for a tropical depression that dissipated over Mindanao :*[[Typhoon Patsy (1970)|1970]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Patsy, which killed at least 262&nbsp;people in the Philippines and Vietnam *{{Anchor|Yolanda}}Yolanda :* [[Tropical Storm Yolanda (1992)|1992]] - a tropical storm that remained well west of Mexico :* [[Yolanda (storm)|2010]] - a non-tropical system that struck [[Europe]] during May 2010. :* [[Typhoon Haiyan|2013]] - Typhoon Haiyan, known in the Philippines as Typhoon Yolanda, was the strongest storm that made landfall on record, killing 5,000 people in the Philippines. *{{Anchor|Yolande}}Yolande :*[[1971–72 South Pacific cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Yolande|1972]] - tropical cyclone in the South Pacific :*[[2002–03 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Yolande|2002]] - tropical storm that passed near Tonga *{{Anchor|Yoning}}Yoning :*[[1964 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Ruby .28Yoning.29|1964]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Ruby, which passed north of Luzon and struck near Hong Kong, killing 730&nbsp;people :*[[1976 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Marge .28Yoning.29|1976]] - PAGASA name for Tropical Storm Marge, which passed east of Luzon and Taiwan :*[[1980 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Cary .28Yoning.29|1980]] - PAGASA name for Tropical Storm Cary, which formed over the Philippines and struck Vietnam :*[[1984 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Clara .28Yoning.29|1984]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Clara, which recurved in the Philippine Sea :*[[1988 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Skip .28Yoning.29|1988]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Skip, which killed 104&nbsp;people while crossing the Philippines *{{Anchor|York}}[[1999 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm York .28Neneng.29|York (1999)]] - moved ashore the Chinese province of Guangdong, killing 15 people *{{Anchor|Yoyong}}[[Typhoon Nanmadol (2004)|Yoyong (2004)]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Nanmadol, the last in a series of four deadly storms that struck the Philippines *{{Anchor|Yoyoy}}[[Typhoon Lupit (2003)|Yoyoy (2003)]] - PAGASA name for Typhoon Lupit, which left heavy damage in the Federated States of Micronesia *{{Anchor|Yunya}}Yunya :*[[Typhoon Yunya (1991)|1991]] - typhoon that struck Luzon at the same time as the eruption of [[Mount Pinatubo#1991 eruption|Mount Pinatubo]], which contributed to [[lehar]]s (landslides) that killed around 300 people :*[[1994 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Yunya .28Norming.29|1994]] - caused landslides on Luzon, killing 11 people *{{Anchor|Yule}}[[1997 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Yule|Yule (1997)]] - formed and remained well east of Japan *{{Anchor|Yuri}}Yuri :*[[Typhoon Yuri (1991)|1991]] - passed near Guam as a powerful typhoon, leaving 90% of the island without power :*[[1994 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Yuri|1994]] - formed and moved eastward away from Japan *{{Anchor|Yutu}}Yutu :*[[2001 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Yutu .28Huaning.29|2001]] - hit Guangdong in southern China :*[[2007 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Yutu .28Amang.29|2007]] - intense typhoon in the Philippine Sea :*[[2013 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Yutu|2013]] - only classified a tropical storm by the JMA; classified as subtropical depression by JTWC :*[[2018 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Yutu (Rosita)|2018]] - a powerful and intense super typhoon which became the strongest storm to affect the [[Northern Mariana Islands]] on record *{{Anchor|Yvette}}Yvette :*[[1992 Pacific typhoon season#Super Typhoon Yvette .28Ningning.29|1992]] - super typhoon that curved away from the Philippines :*[[1995 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Yvette .28Oniang.29|1995]] - struck the Philippines and Vietnam :*[[2016–17 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Yvette|2016]] - struck Western Australia on Christmas Day as a tropical depression *{{Anchor|Yvonne}}Yvonne :*[[1940–49 Pacific typhoon seasons#Tropical Storm Yvonne|1945]] - tropical storm that struck Vietnam :*[[1970–71 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Yvonne-Lise|1971]] - formed in the Australian basin and crossed into the south-west Indian Ocean :*[[1973–74 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Yvonne|1974]] - struck Australia's Cape York Peninsula
==Z== *{{Anchor|Zack}}Zack :*[[1992 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Zack|1992]] - remained over the open western Pacific Ocean :*[[1995 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Zack .28Pepang.29|1995]] - struck the Philippines and Vietnam, killing 110 people *{{Anchor|Zaka}}Zaka :*[[1995–96 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Zaka|1996]] - passed near New Caledonia :*[[2010–11 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Zaka|2011]] - dissipated northeast of New Zealand *{{Anchor|Zane}}Zane :*[[1996 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Zane .28Reming.29|1996]] - typhoon that crossed the Ryukyu Islands :*[[2012–13 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Zane|2013]] - cyclone that developed and dissipated between the coasts of Queensland and Papua New Guinea *{{Anchor|Zeb}}[[Typhoon Zeb|Zeb (1998)]] - intense typhoon that killed 122 people when it struck Luzon *{{Anchor|Zelia}}Zelia :*[[1998–99 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Zelia|1998]] - passed near Cocos Islands :*[[2010–11 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Zelia|2011]] - intense tropical cyclone that brought heavy rainfall to New Zealand as an extratropical cyclone *{{Anchor|Zeke}}Zeke :*[[Typhoon Zeke (1991)|1991]] – passed over the Philippines before hitting Hainan with minimal damage :*[[Tropical Storm Zeke (1992)|1992]] – a tropical storm off the southwestern Mexican coast :*[[Typhoon Zeke (1994)|1994]] – remained east of Japan *{{Anchor|Zelda}}Zelda :*[[Tropical Storm Zelda (1991)|1991]] - left heavy damage in the Marshall Islands :*[[1994 Pacific typhoon season#Super Typhoon Zelda .28Esang.29|1994]] - powerful typhoon that took a large, circuitous track through the western Pacific *{{Anchor|Zena}}[[2015–16 South Pacific cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Zena|Zena (2016)]] - killed two people while passing near Fiji *{{Anchor|Zeta}}[[Tropical Storm Zeta|Zeta (2005)]] - forming in late December 2005 and lasting until early January 2006, it was one of only two Atlantic tropical cyclones to span two calendar years, along with [[Hurricane Alice (December 1954)|Hurricane Alice]] in 1954-55 *{{Anchor|Zia}}[[1999 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Zia|Zia]] - moved across Japan, killing 9 *{{Anchor|Zigzag}}[[2003 Pacific typhoon season#Other storms|Zigzag (2003)]] - PAGASA name for a tropical storm that dissipated over Mindanao *{{Anchor|Zita}}Zita :*[[Tropical Storm Zita (1997)|Zita (1997)]] - killed 345 people when it struck southern China :*[[2006–07 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Zita|2007]] - passed through French Polynesia *{{Anchor|Zoe}}Zoe :*[[1973–74 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Zoe|1974]] - moved along Australia's east coast :*[[Cyclone Zoe|2002]] - [[List of the most intense tropical cyclones|strongest tropical cyclone on record]] in the southern hemisphere, as recorded by atmospheric pressure *{{Anchor|Zola}}Zola :*[[1990 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Zola|1990]] - struck Japan, killing 3 people :*[[1993 Pacific typhoon season#Severe Tropical Storm Zola .28Unsing.29|1993]] - moved across Japan *{{Anchor|Zoraida}}[[Tropical Storm Podul (2013)|Zoraida (2013)]] - PAGASA name for Tropical Storm Podul, which killed 44&nbsp;people while moving through the Philippines and Vietnam *{{Anchor|Zosimo}}[[2004 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Storm Talas .28Zosimo.29|Zosimo]] - PAGASA name for Tropical Storm Talas, which moved through the Marshall Islands *{{Anchor|Zuman}}Zuman :*[[1986–87 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Zuman|1987]] - South Pacific tropical cyclone :*[[1997–98 South Pacific cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Zuman|1998]] - damaging cyclone in New Caledonia and Vanuatu
